Tuesday, 9:40 pm, and our incident channel lights up: “why did the settlement job run twice at midnight.” Nobody answers for six minutes because everybody’s asleep or pretending to be. Turns out our cron logic compared two Date objects across a DST fallback and decided an hour had passed twice. Classic. We've had some version of this bug three times in two years and every time the fix was a duct tape patch on top of date-fns utilities that were already duct tape on top of the built in Date object.
So when Node 26 landed in May with Temporal turned on by default, no flag, no polyfill needed, I finally had an excuse to do the thing I’d been threatening to do since the TC39 proposal was stuck in stage 2 for what felt like a decade. Rip Date out. All of it. Well, most of it.
Why Date Was Always Cursed
Quick reminder of why this needed doing. Date in JavaScript mixes up three concepts that should never have shared one object: a point in time, a wall clock reading, and a timezone. You'd write new Date(2026, 5, 15) and get something that's simultaneously an instant, a calendar date, and implicitly your system's local timezone, whether you wanted that or not. Month is zero indexed because sure, why not. Mutating methods like setMonth return a number instead of a new object, which has caused more bugs in more codebases than I want to think about.
Temporal splits these concepts into actual distinct types. Temporal.Instant for a fixed point in time. Temporal.PlainDate for a calendar date with no timezone attached at all. Temporal.ZonedDateTime when you genuinely need a timestamp plus a timezone. Temporal.Duration for elapsed time that isn't secretly milliseconds pretending to be meaningful.
Here’s the settlement job bug, rewritten:
// old, cursed version
function isNewDay(lastRun, now) {
return lastRun.getDate() !== now.getDate();
}
// this breaks across DST changes and timezone boundaries// Temporal version
function isNewDay(lastRun, now, timeZone) {
const lastZoned = lastRun.toZonedDateTimeISO(timeZone);
const nowZoned = now.toZonedDateTimeISO(timeZone);
return !lastZoned.toPlainDate().equals(nowZoned.toPlainDate());
}The difference isn’t just syntax. toPlainDate() forces you to be explicit about which timezone's calendar you're asking about, so the DST edge case that bit us is structurally impossible to write by accident. You'd have to go out of your way to reintroduce it.
The Migration, or, Three Weekends I Won’t Get Back
I didn’t do a big bang rewrite because nobody has time for that and our test coverage on the date utils folder was, generously, “thin.” Instead I went file by file, starting with anything touching money or SLAs, because that’s where the pain lives.
The biggest practical annoyance: mixing Temporal and Date during the transition. A lot of our third party libraries (looking at you, one calendar picker component nobody remembers installing) still expect Date objects as props. So there's a conversion layer now:
function instantToLegacyDate(instant: Temporal.Instant): Date {
return new Date(instant.epochMilliseconds);
}function legacyDateToInstant(date: Date): Temporal.Instant {
return Temporal.Instant.fromEpochMilliseconds(date.getTime());
}Ugly, but it’s a bridge, not a destination. I’ve got a tracking issue to delete both functions once the calendar picker library ships its own Temporal support, which the maintainer says is “on the roadmap” (translation: check back in a year).
Duration math was the other pleasant surprise. We had a function computing SLA breach windows that used raw millisecond arithmetic and a comment that just said // don't touch this, ask whoever wrote it. The person who wrote it left the company fourteen months ago. Here's the replacement:
const slaWindow = Temporal.Duration.from({ hours: 4, minutes: 30 });
const deadline = ticketCreated.add(slaWindow);
const isBreached = Temporal.Instant.compare(now, deadline) > 0;No more counting zeroes to figure out if someone meant 4.5 hours or 45 hours. The function is genuinely readable by someone who wasn’t there when it was written, which is a low bar that most date code in the wild fails to clear.
What Still Hurts
Not everything is solved. Formatting for display still leans on Intl.DateTimeFormat, and bridging that with Temporal objects requires calling .toString() or passing epoch values around depending on which API you're hitting. The ecosystem is catching up unevenly. Some npm packages have Temporal support in a beta branch, some haven't touched it, and a couple of maintainers have made it very clear in GitHub issues that they'd rather not deal with it until adoption is higher. Fair, honestly. Nobody wants to maintain two parallel APIs forever.
Browser support is close enough to universal to stop worrying about it for anything server rendered, but if you’ve got client code that needs to run on older Safari versions in the wild, you’re still shipping a polyfill for those users. Check your analytics before you assume everyone’s on a browser from this decade.
TypeScript’s types for Temporal are solid, which helped more than I expected. Autocomplete catches a lot of the “wait, does this method return a new object or mutate” confusion before it becomes a 2am Slack message.
Testing This Stuff Without Losing Your Mind
The other change worth mentioning: our test suite for date logic used to mock Date.now() with sinon and pray. Temporal makes this a lot less painful because everything is immutable and comparisons are explicit, so you can just construct the exact instant you want and pass it in rather than fighting a global clock mock.
import { test } from "node:test";
import assert from "node:assert";test("SLA breach triggers after 4.5 hours", () => {
const created = Temporal.Instant.from("2026-06-15T09:00:00Z");
const checkTime = Temporal.Instant.from("2026-06-15T14:00:00Z");
const deadline = created.add({ hours: 4, minutes: 30 });
assert.ok(Temporal.Instant.compare(checkTime, deadline) > 0);
});No monkey patching the global clock, no cleanup step to reset it after the test runs, no flaky failures because some other test in the suite forgot to restore the mock. It’s a small thing, but small things are exactly what accumulate into an afternoon of debugging a test that fails only on Tuesdays.
We also found a nastier class of bug once the immutability forced it into the open: a couple of places were passing a shared date object around and mutating it in place, assuming callers wouldn’t notice. Temporal objects can’t be mutated at all, so those call sites just threw immediately instead of silently corrupting data three functions downstream. Painful for about a day, better for every day after.
So Was It Worth Three Weekends
Ask me in six months when the next timezone bug shows up, because it will, just in some corner we haven’t migrated yet. What I can say is the settlement job hasn’t double run since, and the SLA breach calculation stopped needing tribal knowledge to modify. That’s a decent trade for some weekend hours and a mildly bruised ego about how long we tolerated the old code.
The payments team still brings up the midnight incident whenever they want to rib the backend team. I don’t have a comeback for that one. Some bugs you just have to live down.
